    "en": {
      "title": "Sri Lanka\u2019s presidential vote \u2013 Alahapperuma comes from far behind after Premadasa\u2019s withdrawal",
      "author": "",
      "body_lines": [
        "ECONOMYNEXT \u2013 Sri Lanka\u2019s former Media Minister Dullas Alahapperuma\u2019s chances to win the presidential vote have increased after Opposition Leader Sajith Premadasa withdrew from the presidential race to support his rival, but the outcome will be decided by individual secret votes.",
        "Since Premadasa\u2019s withdrawal, many independent and minority political parties have pledged support to Alahapperuma, but he is not favoured by the majority of the former ruling Sri Lanka Podujana Peramuna (SLPP) lawmakers, a block vote which will be the deciding factor on Wednesday\u2019s vote.",
        "Analysts have come up with their own predictions which show both Alahepperuma and Acting President Ranil Wickremesinghe having equal chances to become the eighth executive president of Sri Lanka.",
        "\u201cWe are confident Dullas-Sajith team will make it through this morning and begin the process to end the Sri Lanka crisis,\u201d Premadasa\u2019s close ally and lawmaker Harsha de Silva tweeted Wednesday (20) morning.",
        "Wickremesinghe\u2019s camp has not commented on their strength, but it believes lawmakers who are attacked and affected by the protesters will not vote for their own SLPP colleague Alahepperuma because Premadasa is now seen close to protesters. (Colombo/Jul20/2022)"
      ],
